Before going much farther, this is a good time to identify the facial artery and vein (A). These vessels will be found just anterior to the masseter muscle, running parallel to its anterior border. The artery will be anterior to the vein.

Feel the pulse of the facial artery at this location on yourself and your lab partner. 
The facial artery is a branch of the external carotid artery (B). Clean and trace the facial artery superiorly to where it ends as the angular artery (C) near the medial canthus of the eye.
The facial vein lies just posterior to the facial artery where the vessels cross the mandible. It is a tributary of the internal jugular vein (D).
When you are done, you will have revealed the entire course of the facial artery and vein over the mandible and face to the medial canthus of the eye.
